Relative housing costs by census tract, Frederick County, Maryland.

RMandava

2023-05-21

Introduction

In this document, I’m going to perform basic analyses of housing costs for renters and homeowners in Frederick County Maryland based on U.S. census tract level data. Above the level of the census block groups and the census blocks, the census tract is the largest census specific geography. I use the median gross rent as a percentage of household income for renters and the median selected cost of housing as a percentage of household income for homeowners to measure housing costs. (See the References section below for discussion of other ways to measure housing costs.)

For those readers unfamiliar with the R statistical software and the additional Tidyverse software I use to manipulate and plot data, I’ve included some additional explanation of various steps. For more information check out the the tutorial “Getting started with the Tidyverse”.

Setup and data preparation

Libraries

I use the following packages for the following purposes:

  • tidyverse: do general data manipulation.

  • tidycensus: retrieve U.S. census data.

  • tigris: retrieve U.S. census geospatial data.

  • sf: manipulate geospatial data.

  • viridis: obtain special color palettes for graphs.

  • knitr: display tabular data.

v21 <- load_variables(2021, "acs5", cache = TRUE)%>%

The census API key is required in the tidycensus and tigris packages. I’ve already obtained and stored such a key so that the functions in the tidycensus or tigris packages can be used.

Data sources

I use data from the following sources; see the References section below for more information:

  • Median gross monthly rents as a percentage of income for 2017-2021 are from table B25071 of the 2021 American Community Survey 5-year estimates, and are accessed via the tidycensus get_acs() function.

  • Median monthly housing costs as a percentage of income for 2017-2021 are from table B25092 of the 2021 American Community Survey 5-year estimates, and are also accessed via the tidycensus get_acs() function.

  • Census tract boundaries are from the U.S. Census Bureau cartographic boundaries data for 2021, and are accessed via the tigris tracts() function.

  • Road geometry is also from the U.S. Census Bureau, and is accessed via the tigris roads() function.

Reading in and preparing the data

In this analysis I primarily look at data at the level of a census tract. There are currently 65 census tracts in Frederick County. Tract-level data is not available in the American Community Survey 1-year estimates, but is available in the 5-year estimates.

As noted in previous analyses I’ve done, a typical census tract in Frederick County contains about 6,000 people, and is roughly comparable in both size and population to a Columbia village.

I use the tidycensus get_acs() function to retrieve median gross rent as a percentage of household income from the 2021 ACS 5-year estimates for all census tracts in Frederick County. This function returns data in tidy format, with the following columns:

  • GEOID. An 12-character geographic ID for the census tract, as discussed above.

  • NAME. The name of the census tract.

  • variable. References the ACS variable being retrieved, in this case “B25071_001”).

  • estimate. The ACS 5-year estimate for the variable’s value.

  • moe. The margin of error for the estimate.

I use estimate and moe to calculate a coefficient of variation cv for the data. The CV can be used to gauge the relative reliability of the estimates, as discussed below.

I similarly use get_acs() to retrieve median selected costs of housing as a percentage of household income for homeowners with and without a mortgage, using variables “B25092_002” and “B25092_003” respectively. Again I calculate CV values for the estimates.

# Median gross rent as a percentage of household income in the past 12 months for all the census tracts in Frederick County, Maryland.

mgrpi_tr <- get_acs(
  year = 2021,
  survey = "acs5",
  geography = "tract",
  state = "MD",
  county = "Frederick",
  variables = "B25071_001"
)%>%
  mutate(cv = 100 * ((moe / 1.645) / estimate))
## Getting data from the 2017-2021 5-year ACS

In order to produce maps of housing costs I need geometry of the cartographic boundaries for all census tracts in Frederick County as of 2021.

I use the tigris function tracts() to return the cartographic boundaries in the form of a table compatible with the sf package. The table as returned for 2021 has a variable GEOID that is identical to the variable of the same name returned by get_decennial() and get_acs(). I don’t need any of the metadata returned with the boundaries, so I retain only GEOID and the geometry itself.

library(tidyverse)
library(tidycensus)
library(tigris)
library(sf)

options(tigris_class = "sf") # Make sure we're using sf for tigris
options(tigris_use_cache = TRUE) # Make sure we cache
#census_api_key("YOURKEYHERE")

map_tr <- tracts(
  year = 2021,
  state = "24",
  county = "021",
  cb = TRUE, class = "sf",
  progress_bar = FALSE
) %>%
  select(GEOID)

map_co <- counties(
  year = 2021,
  state = "24",
  cb = TRUE, class = "sf",
  progress_bar = FALSE
) %>%
  select(GEOID)

To help orient readers as to the locations of the census tracts, I also want any maps generated to also display major roads in Frederick County that correspond in whole or in part to census tract boundaries. I use the tigris function roads() to return geometry for all Frederick County roads.

Because I don’t need or want to display each and every Frederick County road, I use the RTTYP and FULLNAME variables to filter the results to retain only major roads (interstates and U.S. highways) and minor roads (Maryland state routes, and roads with “Pkwy” in their name). I store the geometry for each in separate variables, so that I can plot them at different widths.

all_roads <- roads(state = "24", county = "021", class = "sf", progress_bar = FALSE)

major_roads_geo <- all_roads %>%
  filter(RTTYP %in% c("I", "U")) %>%
  st_geometry()

minor_roads_geo <- all_roads %>%
  filter(RTTYP == "S" | str_detect(FULLNAME, "Pkwy")) %>%
  st_geometry()

Analysis

In answering this question, I perform an analysis: - How is the cost of housing in Frederick County different from one another?

Summary of housing cost statistics

Before I look at relative housing costs within Frederick County, here’s a quick summary of relative housing costs at the county, state, and national level:

The estimated median gross rent as a percentage of household income for the 2017-2021 timeframe was 28.9% for Frederick County, 30.0% for Maryland, and 29.8% for the U.S. overall. The corresponding margins of error were 1.0%, 0.3%, and 0.2% respectively.

The estimated median selected costs of housing as a percentage of household income for owners with mortgages in the 2017-2021 timeframe was 20.4% for Frederick County, 21.0% for Maryland, and 20.9% for the U.S. overall. The corresponding margins of error were 0.5%, 0.1%, and 0.1% respectively.

Finally, the estimated median selected costs of housing as a percentage of household income for owners without mortgages in the 2017-2021 timeframe was 9% for Frederick County, 10.1% for Maryland, and 11% for the U.S. overall. The corresponding margins of error were NA%, 0.2%, and 0.1% respectively.

As discussed previously, there are currently 65 census tracts in Frederick County. For the 2017-2021 timeframe the smallest median gross rent as a percentage of household income for any census tract was 9.0% and the largest 51%. Margins of error for estimates at the census tract level ranged from 1.4% to 84.4%.

For the 2017-2021 timeframe the smallest median selected costs of housing as a percentage of household income for owners with a mortgage for any census tract was 16.8% and the largest 28.2%. Margins of error for estimates at the census tract level ranged from 1.3% to 7.0%.

For the 2017-2021 timeframe the smallest median selected costs of housing as a percentage of household income for owners without a mortgage for any census tract was 9% and the largest 25.6%. Margins of error for estimates at the census tract level ranged from 2.1% to 21.6%.

Reliability of relative housing cost estimates

The reliability of American Community Survey estimates can be judged based on the coefficients of variation. As a rule of thumb, estimates with coefficients of variation less than or equal to 12 are considered to have high reliability, estimates with CVs between 12 and 40 are considered to have medium reliability, and estimates with CVs above 40 are considered to have low reliability.

For the estimates of median gross rent as a percentage of income, the median coefficient of variation is 16 at the tract level, 4 at the county level within Maryland, and 1 at the state level.

For the estimates of median selected cost of housing as a percentage of income for owners with mortgages, the median coefficient of variation is 6 at the tract level, 1 at the county level within Maryland, and 1 at the state level.

For the estimates of median selected cost of housing as a percentage of income for owners without mortgages, the median coefficient of variation is 19 at the tract level, 4 at the county level within Maryland, and 1 at the state level.

The county- and state-level estimates thus all have high reliability, but the estimates at the census tract level are less reliable. That’s why I decided to do this analysis at the level of census tracts as opposed to census block groups, since reliability at the census block group level would be even worse.

The following histogram shows the distribution of coefficients of variation for the tract-level estimates for renters. (By setting the x-axis limit to 100 I eliminate from the histogram one outlier CV that is over 100.)

Frederick County housing costs by census tract

I now want to look at differing median housing costs relative to income across Frederick County. I begin by discarding estimates for any census tracts that have missing coefficients of variation, or for which the CV indicates that the estimate is of low reliability.

mgrpi_tr <- mgrpi_tr %>%
  filter(!is.na(cv) & cv < 40)

mscohpi_m_tr <- mscohpi_m_tr %>%
  filter(!is.na(cv) & cv < 40)

mscohpi_nm_tr <- mscohpi_nm_tr %>%
  filter(!is.na(cv) & cv < 40)

The solid vertical line at 30% shows the level of rent vs. income above which a household is said to be “burdened” with respect to housing costs. Note that there are many census tracts within which the median household is paying well above 30% of household income in gross rents, and is thus considered to be burdened.

The dashed line shows the estimated median gross rent as a percentage of income for all Frederick County households. Half of all households pay less than this percentage, and half more. This value is less than 30%, so less than 50% of Frederick County households overall are housing cost burdened.

Mapping Frederick County housing cost variation

I’m going to show the same information in a map format. First I shall determine the appropriate minimum and maximum limits for the scale to ensure that each map is uniformly sized.

lower_limit <- round(min(
  min(mgrpi_tr$estimate, na.rm = TRUE),
  min(mscohpi_m_tr$estimate, na.rm = TRUE),
  min(mscohpi_nm_tr$estimate, na.rm = TRUE)
) - 4.9, -1)
upper_limit <- round(max(
  max(mgrpi_tr$estimate, na.rm = TRUE),
  max(mscohpi_m_tr$estimate, na.rm = TRUE),
  max(mscohpi_nm_tr$estimate, na.rm = TRUE)
) + 4.9, -1)

The first map sets out for the period from 2017 to 2021, as a percentage of household income, an estimate of the median net rent in Frederick County. I’d rather not try to mark the roads in Frederick County, ’cause it would be a lot of work and make my map look messy. In any event, their intended audience is supposed to know most if not every road by sight.

# Base plot
pl1 <- mgrpi_tr %>%
  right_join(map_tr, by = "GEOID") %>%
  ggplot(aes(fill = estimate, geometry = geometry)) +
  geom_sf(size = 0) +
  geom_sf(data = major_roads_geo, color = "white", size = 1.0, fill = NA) +
  geom_sf(data = minor_roads_geo, color = "white", size = 0.5, fill = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis(option = "plasma", name = "% of Income", limits = c(lower_limit, upper_limit), breaks = seq(lower_limit, upper_limit, 10)) +
  labs(
    title = "2017-2021 Frederick County Relative Housing Costs (Renters)",
    subtitle = "Median Gross Rent as Percentage of Household Income by Census Tract",
       caption = paste0(
         "Data sources:",
         "\n  U.S. Census Bureau, 2021 American Community Survey, Table B25071",
         "\n  U.S. Census Bureau, 2021 cartographic boundaries",

         "\nGray areas indicate missing or unreliable estimates"
       )
  ) +
  theme(plot.caption = element_text(margin = margin(t = 15), hjust = 0)) +

According to the above map, several census tracts in the County are home to renters who have high costs of living. On this map and below, there are grey areas corresponding to census tracts which were not taken into account due to missing or too high coefficients of variation.
